The '''6-ton, 6×6 Truck''' [[List of U.S. military vehicles by supply catalog designation#G500 - G599|(G512, 514, 547, 569)]] was a family of heavy tactical trucks built for the [[United States Armed Forces]] during [[World War II]]. The basic cargo versions were designed to transport a {{convert|12,000|lb|abbr=on}} cargo load over all terrain in all weather. The chassis was built by [[Brockway Motor Company]], [[Corbitt (automobile company)|The Corbitt Company]], [[Four Wheel Drive|The Four Wheel Drive Auto Company (FWD)]], [[Ward LaFrance Truck Corporation]], and [[White Motor Company]]. They were replaced by the [[M54 (truck)|M39 series]] 5-ton trucks in the 1950s.

== History ==
In 1939 the US Army Ordinance Corps set standards for an all-wheel-drive off-road tactical trucks. A 6-ton (5,443kg) payload rated truck to tow anti-aircraft artillery was added. Corbitt, a small company who had sold the US Army trucks since 1917, began delivering 200 prototypes. In 1941 their improved Model 50SD6, with a larger engine and different hood and fenders, was standardized and went into production. Shortly after White began building them, they would be the largest producer. Brockway began in 1942, and FWD in 1945. Ward LaFrance also built the chassis. Seven body types were built, some by more than one manufacturer. All manufacturer’s models were virtually identical, with very minor variations.{{sfnp|Crismon|2001|pp=9, 363, 368-370}}{{sfnp|Doyle|2003|pp=208–212}}

Early models had closed cabs with full doors, in 1942 open cabs with half doors were introduced. Both could be equipped with a ring for a [[.50BMG|.50 cal.]] machine gun. Cranes had an open half-cab.{{sfnp|Doyle|2003|pp=208–212}}
{{sfnp|TM 9-813|1944|p=6}}

== Specifications ==
=== Engine and driveline ===
[[File:Hercules_HXD_engine.jpg|thumb|right|Hercules HXD (right front view)]]
[[File:6-ton winches.jpg|thumb]]

All standardized models used Hercules HXD engines, a [[Engine displacement|{{convert|855|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}}]]
[[Flathead engine|L-head]] [[Straight six engine|inline 6 cylinder]] [[Petrol engine|gasoline engine]] developing [[Horsepower|{{convert|202|hp|kW|abbr=on}}]] at 2100&nbsp;[[Revolutions per minute|rpm]] and {{convert|330|lbfft|0|abbr=on}} of [[torque]] at 900&nbsp;rpm.{{sfnp|TM 9-813|1944|pp=124-125}}

A Fuller 4-speed manual non-synchronized [[Transmission (mechanics)|transmission]] with a very low 1st and direct 4th gear was used. A Timken transfer case had a high and low range, a neutral for [[Power take-off|power take-off (PTO)]] operation, and engaged the front axle. Rear axles were Timken double reduction “pumpkin” type, tractors had heavier rear axles.{{sfnp|Doyle|2003|pp=208–212}}{{sfnp|TM 9-813|1944|pp=25-28}}

=== Chassis ===
Most models had a [[Vehicle frame#Ladder Frame|ladder frame]] with three live axles, the front on [[leaf spring]]s, the rear tandem leaf springs with locating arms. The exception was the crane truck, which had a walking beam rear suspension for stability. {{sfnp|TM 9-813|1944|pp=202, 215, 242-245}}

There were three [[wheelbase]]s. The short, used for prime movers, was {{convert|185|in|m|2}}, the long, used for cranes, was {{convert|197|in|m|2}}, and the extra long, used for bridge erectors, was {{convert|220|in|m|2}}. (Measurements are from the centerline of the front axle to the centerline of rear tandem).{{sfnp|TM 9-813|1944|p=17}}

Prime movers and tankers had 10.00x22 size tires, while bridge, crane, and semi-tractor trucks had 14.00x20s with a larger cross-section. All had dual rear tires. Brakes were [[Air brake (road vehicle)| full air]] with [[drum brake]]s on all wheels. Prime movers had adjustable electrical brake connections for trailer brakes.{{sfnp|Doyle|2003|p=212}}{{sfnp|TM 9-813|1944|pp=224-226, 238}}

Prime movers had a {{convert|25,000|lb|abbr=on}} winch behind the cab, most other trucks had a front-mounted two-drum winch for self-recovery. Trucks converted from prime mover chassis had no winch at all.{{sfnp|TM 9-813|1944|pp=29-30}}

