[[File:6 ton Crane truck.jpg|thumb|right|Crane Trucks]]
[[File:6 ton Tractor truck.jpg|thumb|right|Tractor Truck]]
[[File:6 ton Gasoline tank truck.jpg|thumb|right|Gasoline Tank Truck]]
[[File:6 ton Fire crash truck.jpg|thumb|right|Fire Crash Truck]]
[[File:6 ton Commo van truck.jpg|thumb|right|Prime Mover Van Truck]] 

=== Prime  Mover Cargo Truck ===
Prime movers were used to tow field artillery pieces, they also transported gun crews, equipment, and ammunition. They had a pintle hitch at the rear for towing up to {{convert|40,000|lb|abbr=on}}. Another pintle at the front could be used to emplace the piece. A mid-mounted {{convert|25,000|lb|abbr=on}} winch had a centered cable drum and a capstan on the right side. Pulleys and rollers routed the cable under the body and out the rear frame cross-member. 

With a short wheelbase, mid-mounted winch, and short overhang, the body could only be {{convert|9|ft|m|2|abbr=on}} feet long. Both sides had sideboards with fold down troop seats and bows for a tarpaulin. Two spare tires were mounted inside the body, one along each side. Early models had all steel bodies, in 1942 they were replaced by largely wood types to conserve steel. All Corbitts (3,077) were prime movers, White also built 3,547.{{sfnp|Doyle|2003|pp=208–212}}{{sfnp|Doyle|2015|pp=3, 6-46}}

=== Bridge Erection Truck ===
Built on a long, reinforced chassis, they were used to carry [[Pontoon bridge#Engineer Treadway Bridge Company|treadway pontoon bridges]] for [[Engineer Combat Battalion|combat engineers]]. A large double arm hydraulic boom built by Heil was used to self unload components, often directly into a river. A {{convert|25,000|lb|abbr=on}} winch was mounted at the front. They had an auxiliary air compressor and large reservoir tanks, used to inflate pontoon floats. Brockway built 1,166, White 1,152, Ward LaFrance 589, and FWD 168.{{sfnp|Crismon|2001|pp=368–369}}{{sfnp|Doyle|2015|pp=4,53-87}}{{sfnp|TM 9-813|1944|pp=302–303}}{{sfnp|TM 5-8067|2003|pp=208–209, 212}}{{sfnp|TM 5-272|1944}}

=== Crane Truck ===
Quickway cranes were used by combat engineers to unload and assemble bridge components. The rotating crane was powered by an auxiliary [[International Harvester|IHC]] {{convert|334|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} inline 4 cylinder engine developing {{convert|35|hp|kW|abbr=on}}. As a derrick it could lift {{convert|13,000|lb|abbr=on}} at a minimum radius of {{convert|10|ft|m|2|abbr=on}} and {{convert|5,550|lb|abbr=on}} at a maximum radius of {{convert|25|ft|m|2|abbr=on}}. A shovel, clamshell, dragline, and drilling equipment could also be used. The cab had a windshield on the left side only, in transit the boom went over the right side and was braced to the front bumper. A {{convert|25,000|lb|abbr=on}} winch was mounted on the front. Brockway built 1,224.{{sfnp|Crismon|2001|p=431}}{{sfnp|Doyle|2015|pp=4,88-109}}

=== Tractor Truck ===
As artillery pieces were being towed more often by tracked vehicles, prime mover chassis became available for other uses. In 1945 White built 112 semi-tractors with a fifth wheel and heavier rated Timken axles. Tire size was 14.00x20. Maximum speed was {{convert|40|mph|abbr=on}}, the highest in the series. A {{convert|25,000|lb|abbr=on}} winch was mounted on the front.{{sfnp|Crismon|2001|p=370}}{{sfnp|Doyle|2015|pp=5, 120-128}}

=== Gasoline Tank Truck ===
Wanting a fuel tanker larger than the CCKW, the Army ordered 25 from White. The body had 4 self-sealing tank compartments for a total of {{convert|2,000|usgal|l|abbr=on}}. A bow and canvas top was fitted, so the truck could be disguised as a common cargo truck. Early trucks had a hard cab and a front mounted pintle hitch, later trucks had an open cab and a {{convert|25,000|lb|abbr=on}} front winch. A {{convert|2,000|usgal|l|abbr=on}} gallon trailer could be towed. No follow up orders were made.{{sfnp|Crismon|2001|p=369}}{{sfnp|Doyle|2015|pp=4-5, 110-115}}

=== Fire Crash Truck ===
Fire Crash trucks were used by the Army Air Force to fight fires from airplane crashes. Brockway and Ward LaFrance chassis were equipped with bodies by Mack and [[American LaFrance]] (a separate company), both had auxiliary engines for the pump. This allowed the truck to move while two foam nozzles were being used. American LaFrance used their own 12 cylinder engine and 4 stage pump. Mack used a Continental R-6602 developing {{convert|225|hp|kW|abbr=on}} to drive a Hale centrifugal pump capable of {{convert|325|USgal/min|l/min|abbr=on}} at {{convert|500|psi|Pa|abbr=on}}.{{sfnp|Doyle|2015|pp=5, 116-119}}{{sfnp|TM 9-2800|1947|p=321}}{{sfnp|Vanderveen|2003|p=78}}

=== Prime Mover Van Truck ===
White built communication vans for the Army Air Force on the prime mover wheelbase. Bodies were from [[Superior Coach Company|Superior]] and [[Thomas Built Buses|Thomas]]. They were used to tow and power the SCR-545-A anti-aircraft radar set. White built 1,870.{{sfnp|Crismon|2001|p=369}}{{sfnp|Doyle|2015|pp=3-4, 47-52}}{{sfnp|TM 9-2800|1947|p=304}}

